Today was mostly a planning and concept-clarification session rather than hands-on coding, so this log reflects that.

Spent today refining the direction for my Week 4 capstone project.
Moved away from the earlier Telco Churn idea and explored a text-based Spam Detection (TF-IDF + Naive Bayes) alternative, but worked through why clustering on raw TF-IDF vectors is problematic due to high dimensionality and sparsity, especially on a small dataset.
Went back and forth on whether PCA or TruncatedSVD is more appropriate for sparse text data, and understood the trade-offs of using PCA anyway on a smaller dataset.

Settled on a tabular, numeric-heavy dataset direction instead, since it fits the clustering-plus-classification workflow more cleanly without the text-preprocessing complications.
Clarified that the dataset itself is generalized/likely US-based, not Pakistan-specific, and decided to be upfront about that in the write-up rather than overclaiming direct regional applicability. The methodology is what's meant to be transferable, not the trained model itself.

Worked out the full pipeline structure: K-Means clustering on scaled numeric features to generate a Cluster_ID, which then gets combined with the main features as an engineered input for classification.
Compared Logistic Regression vs Random Forest for this use case. Random Forest likely wins on raw performance, but Logistic Regression has a real edge in interpretability, which matters for a lending-decision context.
Decided to deploy Logistic Regression as the live Streamlit model specifically so I can show per-prediction coefficient contributions, i.e. which features pushed a specific person's prediction up or down, not just a final probability.

Finalized the Streamlit structure as three pages: live prediction with feature contribution breakdown, a cluster visualization page with PCA used only for 2D plotting, and a model comparison page with metrics across classifiers.

